<TITLE> Stocks bounce off early losses </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 24 (bdnews24.com)Stocks shook off the regulator's intervention Tuesday after institutional investors rushed to lock in blue chips of pharmaceuticals, banks and power companies. Pharmaceutical sector heavyweight Square Pharma led the upbeat journey. "It appears that the market has digested the SEC intervention," said Yawer Sayeed, chief executive of AIMS of Bangladesh that manages about Tk 700 million in funds. The SEC directed the shares of AB Bank, BRAC Bank, Power Grid Company of Bangladesh, DESCO and Summit Power to trade on the spot market to help their prices cool down. It became effective from July 23. All the shares except for Power Grid ended higher. Indices on the Dhaka Stock Exchange fell in the morning to midday trade. It regained pace later and traded upbeat toward closing. All Beximco stocks gained on reports that Salman F Rahman, one of the sponsors of Beximco Group, was awarded bail in a case. Some bank and non-bank financial institutions along with life insurance stocks also moved up. "A rush buying from the institutional investors lifted the market," said Salahuddin Ahmed Khan, chief executive of Dhaka Stock Exchange. The DGEN or general index finished at 2378.83, up by 23.03 points or 0.97 percent. The DSI or all-share price index added 18.11 points or 0.94 percent to 1931.54. The DSE-20 blue chip index rallied 22.81 points or 1.06 percent to 2166.78. Of the issues traded, 106 gained, 74 declined and 24 remained unchanged. Turnover rose to Tk 1.87 billion from Monday's Tk 1.78 billion. All the major indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange finished higher although turnover fell to Tk 264.11 million from Tk 279.71 million the previous day. Prices of 66 issues advanced, 40 dropped and six held steady. Bank, leather and footwear and pharmaceutical stocks led the upbeat on the CSE. On the DSE, Square Pharma, which secured Tk 242.54 million in turnover, added 2.86 percent to Tk 5035. Square earlier posted 50 percent cash and 50 percent stock dividends. Southeast Bank, BRAC Bank and National Bank finished next to Square Pharma. Southeast Bank gained 0.48 percent to Tk 564.5. It registered Tk 183.75 million in turnover. BRAC Bank that traded on the spot market moved up 1.66 percent to Tk 913.75 amid investors' rush to trade through cash deals. National Bank grew 1.35 percent to Tk 936. Prime Bank added 0.06 percent to Tk 769. Apex Spinning, Union Capital and Apex Adelchi, Footwear led gainers. TBL, Apex Weaving and GQ Ball Pen were main losers. bdnew
